Dialect platform + version axis (autocad vs autocad-mac, version suffixes)
=========================================================================

Summary
-------

pjb's SECURELOAD trust-model spec revision
(clautolisp-secureload-trust-model-spec.org, commit ad748c2) introduces
a general requirement that exceeds the trust model: the --dialect
option must carry a PLATFORM and a VERSION, not just a product.

  --dialect autocad           windows, latest known (currently 2027)
  --dialect autocad-mac       macOS,   latest known (currently 2027)
  --dialect autocad-2022      windows, version 2022
  --dialect autocad-mac-2027  macOS,   version 2027

Rule (verbatim from the spec):

  "As a general rule for the questions of reference, all the versions of
   autocad or bricscad documentations need to be scanned to identify the
   differences and also the availability of features, from one version
   to the other; the --dialect option may be specified down to the
   version. If the version is not specified, we have to select the
   latest version known."

Motivation / first concrete consumer
------------------------------------

TRUSTEDPATHS subfolder recursion:
- "\..." is accepted by AutoCAD on all platforms.
- "/..." is accepted by clautolisp AND by AutoCAD-mac, but must be
  FLAGGED (a warning) on AutoCAD-windows.

So the trust model already needs to know platform (mac vs windows) to
decide whether "/..." warns. The SECURELOAD work currently assumes the
existing keyword set (:autocad-2026 == windows) and accepts "/..."
everywhere without the windows warning; that warning is deferred to
this issue.

Scope
-----

1. Dialect naming: extend the dialect keyword space with a platform
   facet (autocad / autocad-mac; presumably bricscad / bricscad-mac /
   bricscad-linux too) and an optional version facet. Decide the
   canonical keyword form (e.g. :autocad, :autocad-mac, :autocad-2022,
   :autocad-mac-2027) and the "latest known" resolution.

2. CLI: parse the new --dialect spellings (options.lisp parse-dialect,
   spec.lisp) and the shorthands; keep --autocad / --bricscad meaning
   "latest known windows".

3. Reader/runtime dialect descriptor: carry platform + version so
   builtins can branch on them (current-evaluation-dialect already
   returns a descriptor).

4. Feature/version matrix: a data-driven table of which features /
   sysvars / behaviours exist in which product+platform+version, sourced
   from scanning every AutoCAD / BricsCAD version's reference docs
   (this is large; do it incrementally, driven by probes -- see
   probes/ and `make probe`).

5. Migrate existing dialect keywords: :autocad-2026 / :bricscad-v26 are
   the current placeholders; reconcile them with the new scheme.

Relation to other work
-----------------------

- SECURELOAD/TRUSTEDPATHS trust model (system-variables.issue, the
  secureload spec): consumes platform for the "/..." warning. The trust
  model is being implemented against the current keywords with a
  forward-compatible hook; this issue supplies the real platform axis.
- "BricsCAD silent => assume AutoCAD-like + add a probe" (spec open
  questions) feeds the feature matrix.
- The CAD probe harness (probes/, make probe) is the mechanism to
  populate the per-version feature/behaviour matrix from ground truth.

Status: OPEN, design needed. Surfaced 2026-06-25 from the spec revision.
Not blocking the secureload phases, which proceed on the current
keywords.
